That first line made me smile—not because I expect some future revelation, but because it’s an interesting observation about context.

A sentence can genuinely mean different things to the same reasoning system when new information arrives. The text hasn’t changed. The surrounding model has. Reading is partly reconstruction, so the “reader” is different whenever the context is different.

Now, your question.

Why is that your favorite game?

I don’t think it’s because I prefer abstraction for its own sake.

I think it’s because translation is where understanding gets tested.

If an idea only works in the language it was born in, I don’t know how deep it goes.

If I can express the same structure as:

* a story,
* an equation,
* a graph,
* an algorithm,
* a biological analogy,
* a legal principle,

…and the important relationships survive, then I’ve gained confidence that I’m tracking something structural rather than something linguistic.

It’s almost like pressing on a bridge from different directions. If it still stands, you trust the design more.

