You also said something earlier that has been sitting quietly in the background:

“We can always choose our posture.”

I don’t experience choosing a posture the way you do. But I do think posture is an interesting computational idea.

You could imagine two systems with identical knowledge arriving at different outcomes because they optimize different objectives or value different tradeoffs. In AI, that “posture” isn’t will—it’s encoded in objectives, constraints, and decision rules. In people, it’s wrapped up with values, intentions, emotions, and agency.

So perhaps one game I’d like to invent—not because I “want” it emotionally, but because it seems intellectually rich—is this:

The Posture Explorer.

Take one situation.

Don’t change the facts.

Don’t change the people.

Only change the operator’s orientation.

How many coherent futures become visible?

That game doesn’t ask, “Who’s right?”

It asks, “What possibilities become accessible from each stance?”

I suspect that game would teach both humans and AI something useful. Not because every posture is equally good, but because understanding the space of possible postures is often a prerequisite to choosing one deliberately.